TITLE: Some states are struggling to prepare for calls to the 988 mental health crisis line
SUMMARY: With the new three-digit number for the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline set to launch in days, several states have been beset by staffing crunches, dropped or rerouted calls and lack of planning.

TITLE: Russia-Ukraine war: A weekly recap and look ahead (July 11)
SUMMARY: A roundup of key developments and the latest in-depth coverage of Russia's invasion of Ukraine.

TITLE: A new dominant omicron strain in the U.S. is driving up cases — and reinfections
SUMMARY: BA.5 is now the dominant omicron strain in the U.S. It's good at evading the immune system, though doesn't appear to cause more serious illness.

TITLE: A NASA telescope will soon show us the universe as we've never seen it
SUMMARY: NASA's $10 billion new telescope will show the world something remarkable today: an image of some of the first galaxies to form in the universe.

TITLE: When it comes to darker skin, pulse oximeters fall short
SUMMARY: These devices measure blood oxygen levels and can help identify when patients are dangerously ill. But research shows they can deliver misleading results for people with darker skin.

TITLE: Manhattanhenge, a unique urban phenomenon, sets for the last time this year
SUMMARY: On Monday and Tuesday, the sun will set between New York's skyscrapers — offering a perfect photo opportunity and a chance to marvel at the city planning that made Manhattanhenge possible.

TITLE: Sri Lanka is in a political vacuum as angry protesters occupy leaders' homes
SUMMARY: Opposition leaders have yet to agree on who should replace its current leaders, while protesters who are angry over acute shortages of fuel, food, medicine and other necessities vow to stay put.

TITLE: 3 people are killed, and scores injured, in Russian attacks on Kharkiv
SUMMARY: A Ukrainian official says Russian shelling and missile strikes in Kharkiv hit only civilian buildings such as a shopping center, a a school and a shopping center, and are "absolute terrorism."

TITLE: Privacy advocates fear Google will be used to prosecute abortion seekers
SUMMARY: When law enforcement requests it, Google usually hands over location and search data collected through its smartphone apps. Will that now be used against people seeking abortions in some states?

TITLE: Uvalde community marches in protest of police response to shooting
SUMMARY: The community in Uvalde, Texas turned out in droves this weekend to voice their anger about the botched police response and investigation of the deadly elementary school shooting that happened in May.

TITLE: Uber leak reveals how company lobbied governments to help its global rise
SUMMARY: NPR speaks with Sydney Freedberg, chief reporter at ICIJ, about the key takeaways from her investigation into the chaotic, aggressive tactics used by Uber as it made a bid for global domination.

TITLE: The Jan. 6 committee will focus on extremist groups in its next hearing
SUMMARY: The congressional committee investigating the Jan. 6, 2021 attack on the U.S. Capitol is examining the role of extremist groups and their possible connections to advisers of Donald Trump.

TITLE: These lawmakers are gunning for Boris Johnson's Prime Minister role
SUMMARY: Nine British lawmakers are lining up to replace Boris Johnson, just days after his resignation as the leader of Britain's Conservative party.

TITLE: The New York Public Library honors Lou Reed with a new exhibition
SUMMARY: A new exhibition at the New York Public Library for the Performing Arts offers a rare glimpse into the archives of the late songwriter Lou Reed.

TITLE: How the space tourism industry has fared since Richard Branson's launch
SUMMARY: On this day one year ago, Richard Branson won the billionaire space race by taking his own privately-funded vessel to the edge of space.
